@section @strong{battle-rage} and his joystick rules


@quotation

@strong{battle-rage} has some rules for playing with the joystick.

According to the fact that you have @strong{2 hands} and @strong{2 foots} (exclude for the physic handicap).

@strong{battle-rage} follow @strong{the same logic} for the @emph{joystick} buttons @strong{logic}:


@itemize +

@item 
The @strong{back hand} from your fighter is @strong{activate} by @code{pressing} the @emph{A} button from the @emph{joystick}.

@item 
The @strong{front hand} from your fighter  is @strong{activate} by @code{pressing} the @emph{X} button from the @emph{joystick}.

@item 
The @strong{front foot} from your fighter is @strong{activate} by @code{pressing} the @emph{B} button from the @emph{joystick}.

@item 
The @strong{back foot} from your fighter is @strong{activate} by @code{pressing} the @emph{Y} button from the @emph{joystick}.
@end itemize

@*note: 
You can sea that like a cross which @strong{X} axis is are the foots and the @strong{Y} axis the hands.


You can use @strong{combinations} by adding a direction from the @strong{directional keypad} to the used button.

This will generate different kicks for every combination.

@strong{Finally} all combination make sens, @emph{per example}:

Pressing the @strong{Up} arrow and an @strong{hand button} will produce an @strong{uppercut},

and pressing the :@strong{Back arrow} and a @strong{foot kick} will produce a @strong{return foot kick}.

@cartouche
@quotation Warning 
because @code{nothing is perfect} it can happen that a combination don't really

represent what it should like explain above.

But @strong{I guarantee} that it really @strong{doesn't happen often} and that the replacement @strong{is near from your expecting}.

And some kicks have fallbacks: this mean that 2 differents combination can give the same kick: not often.

All according the fighter.
@end quotation
@end cartouche

@*note: 
Because it's easier to press a button instead of using a combination the combinations inflict more damage.


@cartouche
@quotation Note 
This logic is follow for every @strong{joystick} model since you have to configure your @strong{joystick} first.

But you can @strong{reconfigure} your @strong{joystick} if you make a misstake during the configuration phase.
@end quotation
@end cartouche
@end quotation

