@section Technical notes about joystick handle.


@quotation

Internally @strong{battle-rage} suppose that the buttons @emph{A}, @emph{B}, @emph{Y} and @emph{Y} have all a value comprise between included @emph{[0-3]} like the most @emph{joysticks} does.

Internally @strong{battle-rage} suppose that directional pad is implemented as 2 axis (@emph{B} and @emph{Y} for the @strong{X} axis and @emph{A} and @emph{X} for the y axis).

But you can predict @strong{nor} the @code{SDL2}: if an axis number will be the @strong{X} or the @strong{Y} most common joytsick use 0 for @strong{X} and 1 for @strong{Y}...

But the sticks: analogical and digital are taking in charge, because with @strong{battle-rage} you must configure you joystick the first time you plug it.

And the big problem is that some joystick doesn't respect at all this rules.

I can only test this values which are right for my test @emph{joysticks} (2 joysticks which works differently).

So if your @emph{joystick} work otherwise than with this values for this set of buttons or axis @strong{it won't work at all !}

This fact is coming from that I use an @code{Input_Handler} written by @strong{Shaun Mitchell}, for his book @code{SDL Game Development (june 2013) [Packt Pusblishing]}.

I @strong{enhance} this @code{Input_Handler} to take in charge the most of joytsick possible: The most common.

Even if the base joystick for @strong{Shaun Mitchell} (an @code{X Box 360} @strong{joystick}) won't work with @strong{battle rage} because of the fail of one axe.

But you can play @strong{battle-rage} with an @code{X Box 360} @strong{joystick} but the @strong{Y} axis won't work !

@*note: 
Great thanks to @strong{Shaun Mitchell} for his book and code writing and his code.

@end quotation

